para.p:
Vaccines keep us safe against harmful diseases by increasing the natural defence of our body and inducing immunity to various infections (
            , 
          ). Every licensed vaccine goes through rigorous testing over numerous trial phases before being approved for use by regulators. Nonetheless, adverse events following immunisation could occur, although they are typically modest and transient, like a painful arm or a low-grade fever. Though relatively rare, more severe side effects may occur. Following approval, vaccine safety surveillance services continue to scan and analyse data from a variety of sources for any signs that a vaccine might have unexpected harmful consequences on health, or an increase in incidence or severity of known reactions, known as post-licensure surveillance.

In order to perform post-licensure vaccine safety signal detection, researchers propose diverse approaches that involve various statistical methods (
            , 
          ), techniques, and measures in original, modified, or combined forms. Research and vaccine surveillance groups may also impose necessary modifications to the approaches during implementation, addressing their organisational strengths and limitations, availability of data, and resources. Note, unlike the works performed so far in the literature, we are targeting a unique aspect of the implementation such as strengths, variations and limitations of data due to organisational factors.

Key statistical measures and techniques used in post-licensure vaccine surveillance include Proportional Reporting Ratio (PRR) (
            , 
          ), Cumulative Sum (CUSUM) (
            , 
          ), Reporting Odds Ratio (ROR) (
            , 
          ), Empirical Bayesian Geometric Mean (EBGM) (
            , 
          ), Chi-Square, and MaxSPRT (
            , 
          )-a specialised variation of Sequential Probability Ratio Test (SPRT) (
            , 
          ) proposed by Wald.

Sequential analysis for post-market surveillance evolved to enable early detection of rare adverse events while controlling error rates. An important aspect of vaccine surveillance is the continuous monitoring of adverse events that vaccinees may experience when vaccines are administered, through a continuous sequential analysis that detects a signal when adverse events exceed the probability that they occur by chance (
            , 
          ). Sequential Probability Ratio Test (SPRT) (
            , 
          ) was proposed by Wald to detect adverse events through hypothesis testing. It assumes fixed alternatives and known expected event rates and is appropriate for sequentially independent and identically distributed (iid) data, which implies that the data comes from the same distribution. SPRT is used for surveillance to test if the null hypothesis (no vaccine safety signal or the vaccine is safe), is more likely than the alternative hypothesis (there is a vaccine safety signal). However, SPRT is highly sensitive to the relative risk chosen in the alternative hypothesis construction, which makes it difficult to use for ongoing, routine surveillance.

To further improve control over false positives across multiple looks at data, alpha spending functions were introduced. These functions (e.g., power-type, Pocock (
            , 
          ), O’Brien-Fleming (
            , 
          )) spread the allowable Type I error across time, with concave forms (


              <
              ρ
              1


        ) minimizing expected time to signal (ETS) and convex ones (


              >
              ρ
              1


        ) minimizing expected sample size (ESS). Exact optimization of alpha spending using linear programming (Silva et al., 2020) enables designs that minimize ETS while controlling Type I and Type II errors and sample sizes, and maximizing statistical power, outperforming classical methods.

Note that it is evident from (
            , 
          ) that alpha spending is implicitly defined by sequential test plans, regardless of the test statistic scale that is selected. This can be readily illustrated with the R Sequential (
            , 
          ) package. However, since identical alpha spending produces equivalent results across all scales, the practical lesson is not the test statistic selected but rather the careful selection of a near-optimal alpha spending plan. The package integrates Silva and Kulldorff’s (
            , 
          ) methodological advancements.

A significant improvement is the replacement of the linear interpolation method suggested by Kulldorff et al. (
            , 
          ) with a bisection procedure to precisely compute exact critical values (CVs). This method may result in infinite loops depending on the fixed expected number of events. Moreover, Silva and Kulldorff (
            , 
          ) showed that, in contrast to depending on the continuous critical values that  (
            , 
          ) had previously tabulated, employing group sequential tests with unpredictable sample sizes through alpha spending functions greatly improves statistical power.

Silva et al.’s extensive guide (
            , 
          ) on planning sample sizes and the alpha spending approach in sequential analysis plays a crucial role in maintaining the desired statistical power. They present detailed methodological insights and introduce optimized alpha spending plans to minimize the expected time to signal (ETS) and expected sample size (ESS). However, while Silva et al.’s work expertly addresses statistical optimizations, building on it, our paper takes a more practical, step-by-step approach tailored for real-world implementation, particularly highlighting common challenges such as data wrangling and preprocessing that arise in operational vaccine safety surveillance systems like SAEFVIC.

Moreover, Leite et al. (
            , 
          ) present a comprehensive systematic review of real-world applications of statistical methods in vaccine safety surveillance, presenting a variety of statistical tools and approaches. Their work outlines practical surveillance methods using electronic health records and provides foundational insights into the surveillance landscape. In contrast, our manuscript uniquely integrates these surveillance methods into a hands-on, comprehensive framework, clearly detailing implementation steps, parameter selection, and strategies for addressing common real-world issues like reporting delays and missing data.

By explicitly addressing these pragmatic considerations and providing a comprehensive, illustrative approach to sequential analysis for vaccine safety, our manuscript offers complementary value to existing tutorials and reviews. Thus, our paper serves not as a replacement but rather as an essential operational extension to the seminal methodological contributions of Silva et al. (
            , 
          ) and the foundational review by Leite et al. 
            (
            )
          . It is worth noting that the R Sequential package (
            , 
          ) is central to the sequential surveillance system developed to enhance analysis of SAEFVIC data; all data analyses, experimental results, visualizations, and related research presented in this paper were conducted using this package.

We start with the difference in the calculation of the parameters for SPRT and MaxSPRT. In both Wald’s SPRT (
            , 
          ), and Kulldorff’s MaxSPRT (
            , 
          ), the number of adverse events is considered to be random, while the cumulative person-time or the cumulative number of vaccinations, if the follow-up time per vaccination is uniform, is considered to be fixed. The predicted number of adverse events under the null hypothesis is then considered to be a known function of the total person-time and certain possible confounding variables like age, sex, and location. Figure  denotes this variation by the first branching that occurs for sequential analysis between SPRT and MaxSPRT. Note, another factor that signifies the difference is, SPRT is highly sensitive to the relative risk chosen in the alternative hypothesis and cannot deal with composite alternatives.

Furthermore, the dependence and sufficiency of the comparator data lead to another branching: (i) Conditional MaxSPRT (cMaxSPRT) and (ii) unconditional/conventional MaxSPRT (we refer to it as pMaxSPRT for the sake of simplicity). For the scenario when the background information is insufficient and conditional on an event, Li et al. developed conditional MaxSPRT (cMaxSPRT) (
            , 
          ), where it factors in the number of adverse events in the historical data and the surveillance population and computes the cumulative person-time it took to observe so many events as the random variable.

